text: Cite this: RSC Adv., 2017, 7, 36335 Received 17th May 2017 Accepted 4th July 2017 Tuberculosis (TB), caused by the airborne pathogen Mycobacte- rium tuberculosis (MTB) remains a major global health problem. With 1.4 million deaths in 2015, it is still one of the top ten deadly diseases worldwide.1 Antibiotics are the mainstay for the treat- ment of TB as the only vaccine currently available (the BCG) does not prevent the disease in adults.2 First-line drugs, namely isoniazid, rifampicin, ethambutol and pyrazinamide, are eﬀective in treating TB. However, long duration of treatment (3–6 months) and noncompliance from patients have resulted in the emer- gence of drug resistant strains that are diﬃcult to kill, and pose a serious threat to global TB control.3,4 Emergence of multi-drug resistant (MDR), extensively drug resistant (XDR) and now totally drug resistant (TDR) strains is on the rise globally.5–7 Therefore, the need of the hour is to discover eﬃcient novel molecules that have novel targets in the bacterium. aMycobacterium Research Laboratory, Rajiv Gandhi Centre for Biotechnology, Trivandrum, Kerala, India. Anti-microbial activity of chrysomycin A produced by Streptomyces sp. against Mycobacterium tuberculosis† Balaji Muralikrishnan, Ranjit Ramachandran,a Sabu Thomas,b Syed G. Dastager,e K. Santhosh Kumar,c Ravi Shankar Lankalapalli Limited eﬃcacy of the BCG (Bacillus Calmette–Gu´erin) vaccine against adult tuberculosis and the emergence of resistance to existing anti-tuberculosis drugs compel discovery of novel antibiotics against Mycobacterium tuberculosis. Actinomycetes are still an attractive platform for the discovery of new antimicrobials, especially from untapped natural hotspots, despite the belief that they are an exhausted resource after repeated re-discoveries. Herein we report the isolation and identiﬁcation of chrysomycin A from an actinomycete isolated from a coastal area in Kerala. We show for the ﬁrst time that it has antimycobacterial activity. It was found to be bactericidal to planktonic and intracellular M. tuberculosis with an MIC of 3.125 mg mL(cid:1)1; it is non-hemolytic and has negligible cytotoxicity. The actinomycete that produces chrysomycin A was found to be a Streptomyces sp. through 16S rRNA gene sequencing. ‡a Vipin Mohan Dan,‡a J. S. Vinodh,a Vellekkatt Jamsheena,d d and Ramakrishnan Ajay Kumar*a Actinomycetes have provided us with diﬀerent classes of antibiotics that play a critical role in treating infectious diseases.8 They are the source of more than 45% of all known antibiotics and 90% of usable antibiotics available in the market.9,10 This is mainly due to their capacity to produce versatile bioactive through their resourceful biosynthetic gene clusters.11 We hypothesized that ecological biodiversity hotspots such as coastal areas and tropical forests could harbour new strains of actinomycetes from which novel anti-mycobacterials could be isolated.

In this study, we screened culture ltrates of four hundred actinomycetes isolated from coastal areas and Western Ghats of Kerala, India. Ethyl acetate extract of a Streptomyces sp. OA161, was found to inhibit virulent laboratory strain MTB H37Rv. The active principle was puried, subjected to structural character- ization and identied as chrysomycin A. This is the rst report that chrysomycin A has anti-MTB activity. It was found to be non-cytotoxic to myoblast and epithelial cells and did not lyse red blood cells. Results and discussion Screening of culture ltrate extracts for antimicrobial activity Among four hundred isolates of actinomycetes screened for their antimicrobial activity, ethyl acetate extract of the culture ltrate of the isolate OA161 was found to inhibit the growth of MTB in vitro (ESI Data 1†). The antimicrobial activity assay was extended to a panel of seven more microbes and the results revealed that it inhibited growth of Gram-positive bacteria but not of Gram-negative bacteria (Table 1). Based on the results, RSC Adv., 2017, 7, 36335–36339 | 36335 M. smegmatis was used as a surrogate organism to identify the active principle in the extract as the assay using MTB at every step of activity-guided separation was laborious and time- consuming. The ethyl acetate extract was fractionated using thin layer chromatography and subsequent bioautography with M. smegmatis revealed an inhibitory zone and the spot was named AMF (antimycobacterial fraction) (ESI Data 2†). Subse- quently, the anti-MTB activity of AMF was conrmed by resa- zurin microtitre assay (REMA). Identication of the active principle

Separation of AMF using HPLC revealed two prominent peaks with retention times 26.4 minutes (compound 2) and 28.7 minutes (compound 1, ESI Data 3†). While the molecule eluted at 26.4 minutes had negligible activity, the one that eluted at 28.7 minutes had strong anti-MTB activity. The active principle was subjected to structural characterization by extensive NMR analysis which helped in identication of compound 1 as chrysomycin A (Fig. 1) which was further conrmed by comparison of the NMR data with that in the published literature12–15 (ESI Data 4–6†). The AMF, yellow solid (18 mg) aer separation through HPLC yielded compound 1 (2.5 mg) and compound 2 (9.5 mg), respectively. Antimycobacterial activity of chrysomycin A Chrysomycin A was tested for antimycobacterial activity against MTB by REMA. Planktonic MTB was inhibited by the molecule (cid:1)1 and the same MIC was at an MIC of 3.125 mg mL observed with commercially available chrysomycin A (Abcam). OA161 The partial 16S rRNA gene sequence of our isolate was submitted to GenBank, NCBI (accession number, KX364040). It is 1410 bp in length and 99.07% similar to that of Streptomyces smyrnaeus. A phylogenetic tree was generated using neighbor joining method19 using MEGA 7 soware and the isolate forms a separate clade that is characteristic of a separate species (ESI Data 7†). Experimental General procedures, strains, cell lines and chemicals

Mycobacterium tuberculosis H37Rv was grown in Middlebrook 7H9 medium (Difco) supplemented with 10% OADC (Difco). Other bacteria used in this study are Mycobacterium smegmatis mc2 155, Staphylococcus aureus ATCC 25953, MRSA (methicillin resistant Staphylococcus aureus) clinical strain C10, VRE (vancomycin resis- tant Enterococcus faecalis) clinical strain E8, E. coli ATCC 25922, Pseudomonas aeruginosa clinical strain R8 and Vibrio cholera N16961 and were grown in Luria Bertani broth (HiMedia, Mum- bai). The clinical strains were a kind gi from the Department of Microbiology, Government Medical College, Trivandrum. Nalidixic acid, nystatin, gentamycin, phorbol 12-myristate 13-acetate (PMA) and resazurin were purchased from Sigma; Cell lines L6 (rat myoblast), SW480 (epithelial cell from colon) and THP-1 (Human monocytes) were obtained from National Centre for Cell Science, Pune, India. Cell lines were maintained in RPMI1640 (Sigma) or DMEM (Dulbecco's Modied Eagle's Medium, Gibco) with 10% FBS (Gibco). The extracts and antibiotics were prepared in DMSO and the nal concentration of DMSO used in the assays was 2% whenever used for antimicrobial activity. Isolation of actinomycetes

About 10 grams of soil samples were collected in sterile bags from the sub-soil of diﬀerent ecological niches and were dried (cid:1)1), under shade. This was suspended in sterile water (1 gm mL serially diluted and plated on selective solid growth media (starch casein agar/actinomycetes isolation agar/ISP-2/ISP-7) (cid:1)1) and nystatin (50 with or without nalidixic acid (100 mg mL (cid:1)1) and incubated at 25 (cid:4)C for 2 weeks. Once chalky mg mL colonies appeared, they were further puried on ISP-2 agar. The RSC Adv., 2017, 7, 36335–36339 | 36337 pure colonies were stored in the form of stabs or as glycerol stocks at 4 (cid:4)C and (cid:1)20 (cid:4)C, respectively. Purication of anti-mycobacterial principle Single colony of the actinomycete isolate (OA161) was inocu- lated in modied ISP-2 medium (50 mL) and grown at 30 (cid:4)C on a shaker incubator (250 rpm). Two glass marbles were intro- duced into the medium to prevent clumping of the culture. Aer 6 days, the culture ltrate was prepared by centrifugation of the culture at 6000 rpm for 15 minutes at room temperature fol- lowed by ltration through Whatman 3 lter paper, and passing through 0.2 mm membrane lter. The supernatant was frozen at (cid:1)80 (cid:4)C before lyophilization. The lyophilized powder of the culture ltrate was extracted with ethyl acetate, chloroform, acetone and methanol and these extracts were concentrated under vacuum and used in the antimicrobial assay.

Resazurin microtitre assay (REMA) The assay was carried as described by Martin et al.20 Briey, MTB H37Rv and M. smegmatis were grown in Middlebrook 7H9 medium, turbidity of the culture was adjusted to McFarland standard 1 and further diluted 20 times. For other test strains, Luria Bertani broth (HiMedia) was used for growth. One hundred microlitre of the diluted culture was transferred to the wells of a 96 well microtitre plate (Thermo Fisher). The extracts and puried active principle were dissolved in DMSO and added (cid:1)1 in to a nal concentrations of 200 mg mL a nal volume of 200 mL per well. The plates were incubated for 7 days, with negative (no drug) and positive controls (rifampicin (cid:1)1). MIC was determined aer the and ciprooxacin at 1 mg mL addition of Resazurin (0.25% solution in water) on the 8th day which either remains blue or changes to pink (aer 24 hours) based on the viability of the bacteria. Blue indicates that the bacteria are susceptible (inhibition), and pink indicates the bacteria are resistant to killing (viable) by the extract. Thin layer chromatography and bioautography

Normal phase Silica gel 60 F254 aluminum TLC plates (Merck, India) were used to fractionate the ethyl acetate extract of the culture ltrate of the isolate. Hexane : Acetone (1 : 1) was used as the mobile phase. The TLC plate was allowed to develop in a sterile, saturated closed chamber for 35 minutes. The frac- tionated TLC plate was overlayed with Muller Hinton so agar containing S. aureus or M. smegmatis. This was allowed to solidify and incubated for 24 hours (S. aureus) or 36 hours (M. smegmatis) at 37 (cid:4)C. The active fraction was named AMF (anti- mycobacterial fraction) and this was subjected to HPLC. Purication and characterization of the active principle General procedures. Shimadzu HPLC instrument with C18- phenomenex reverse phase column (250 (cid:5) 21.2 mm, 5 mm) was used for purication of the extract using acetonitrile (ACN) and water. 1H and 13C NMR spectra were recorded at 500 MHz and 125 MHz on a Bruker DRX 500 NMR instrument (Bruker, Rheinstetten, Germany). Deuterated acetone ((CD3)2CO) was 36338 | RSC Adv., 2017, 7, 36335–36339 used for recording the NMR spectrum, chemical shis are given in parts per million (ppm), and coupling constants in Hz. HR- ESI-MS analysis was performed on a Thermo Scientic Exac- tive mass spectrometer with ions given in m/z.

Isolation and identication of the active principle. The AMF (yellow solid) was identied as a mixture of two closely related compounds by TLC and 1H-NMR. The compound mixture was dissolved in acetonitrile (3 mL) and then subjected to purica- tion by reverse-phase preparative HPLC with a gradient program comprising of mobile phase system: solvent A (water) and solvent B (ACN). The linear gradient started with 35% B at 0 min to 80% B for 30 min, and 100% B up to 35 minutes at a ow rate (cid:1)1, monitored at 254 nm. Three major peaks were of 7 mL min identied at a retention time of 26.4 minutes, 28.7 minutes, and 30.1 minutes (ESI Fig. 3†). The compound eluted at 28.7 minutes was found to inhibit MTB H37Rv in vitro and therefore was subjected to characterization by 1H, 13C, 2D NMR and mass spectrometry. Colony forming unit (CFU) count assay. McFarland standard 1 of mid-log phase MTB H37Rv culture was diluted 20 times and treated with chrysomycin A at varying concentrations (cid:1)1) at 37 (cid:4)C for 6–48 hours. Rifampicin (1 mg (3.125(cid:1)31.25 mg mL (cid:1)1) served as positive control and 2% DMSO as negative mL control. All the treated and untreated cultures were diluted further and plated on 7H10 agar containing 0.1% casitone (Difco). The cfus were counted aer 3 weeks.

Anti-mycobacterial activity on intracellular MTB. Twenty thousand THP-1 cells were seeded and were induced with PMA (cid:1)1) for 18–24 hours to diﬀerentiate them into (20 ng mL macrophages. These cells were infected with MTB H37Rv at an MOI of 20 : 1. Four hours aer infection, the external bacteria (which were not phagocytosed) were treated with gentamycin (cid:1)1), and the cells were subsequently treated with (45 mg mL (cid:1)1). chrysomycin A (3.125 mg mL (cid:1)1) were taken as Macrophages treated with rifampicin (1 mg mL positive control and untreated macrophages as negative control. These were incubated at 37 (cid:4)C for 48 hours and lysed with distilled water. The lysate was plated on 7H10 agar con- taining 0.1% casitone (Difco) and the colonies were counted aer 3–4 weeks of incubation at 37 (cid:4)C. MTT assay. The assay was carried out as described by van Meerloo et al.21 Briey, 10 000 cells were seeded per well in a 96 well plate in triplicates. They were treated with chrysomycin A at (cid:1)1) and incubated for diﬀerent concentrations (1–31.25 mg mL 48 hours at 37 (cid:4)C in the presence of 5% CO2. Twenty microlitre of MTT (3-(4,5-dimethylthiazole-2-yl)-2,5-diphenyl tetrazolium (cid:1)1) was added to each well and aer bromide) dye (5 mg mL 4 hours, the reaction was terminated by adding 200 mL of iso- propanol and this dissolves the formazan crystals. This was read at 540 nm on an ELISA reader (Bio-Rad).

Hemolysis assay. The assay was carried out as described by Evans et al.22 with minor modications. Briey, 10% (v/v) fresh suspension of human erythrocytes in phosphate buﬀered saline (PBS, pH 7.2) was incubated with various concentrations of (cid:1)1) at 37 (cid:4)C for 1 hour. One chrysomycin A (2–31.25 mg mL percent SDS (w/v) in water served as positive control and PBS served as negative control. The suspensions were centrifuged This journal is © The Royal Society of Chemistry 2017 (3000 (cid:5) g) for 5 minutes at room temperature and the super- natant was read at 595 nm to measure the amount of hemo- globin released. Hemolysis was interpreted in percentage aer calculating it from three individual experiments.

Sequencing of 16S rRNA and polyketide synthase II alpha subunit genes. Genomic DNA was isolated from the isolate OA161 as described by Lee et al.23 The 16S rRNA gene was amplied with universal primers (ESI Table 2†). Fiy microlitre amplication reaction had 1 mL template DNA (50–200 ng), 10 mL 10(cid:5) PCR buﬀer with MgCl2 (Sigma), 1 mL of forward and reverse primer (20 mM) each, 2 mL dNTP mix (5 mM), 1 U Taq DNA polymerase (Sigma) and 34 mL sterile MilliQ water. The reaction conditions were: initial denaturation at 95 (cid:4)C for 5 minutes, followed by 30 cycles of denaturation at 95 (cid:4)C for 30 seconds, annealing at 54 (cid:4)C for 30 seconds and extension at 72 (cid:4)C for 45 seconds. A nal extension was performed at 72 (cid:4)C for 7 minutes. For polyketide synthase II the amplication reaction conditions alpha subunit gene, remained the same except that the annealing temperature was 62 (cid:4)C. The products were electrophoresed on a 1% agarose gel containing ethidium bromide and visualized under UV light. The PCR product was puried using GE Healthcare gel band purica- tion kit and sequenced directly using a Taq BigDye Terminator Cycle Sequencing Kit in ABI automated DNA sequencer (Applied Biosystems). Both genes were sequenced with diﬀerent forward and reverse sequencing primers to cross check the sequence. The sequences were compared with help of Ez-Taxon and BLAST database, respectively.

Chrysomycin A, isolated from a new species of Streptomyces, showed bactericidal activity against planktonic as well as (cid:1)1. This is the rst intracellular MTB at an MIC of 3.125 mg mL report of chrysomycin A possessing anti-MTB activity. Conﬂicts of interest The authors declare that there are no conicts of interest.
